</div><a id="comment-3334784"></a>


<div class="non_toggle_area" id="comment-3334784">
  <div class="non_toggle_label">
       <span class="scomments_info">Sat, 03/16/2013 - 06:04 | <a href="/news/2013-03-15/guest-post-what-world-bitcoin#comment-3334784" class="active">3334784</a></span>
              <b><a href="/users/royal-wulff" title="View user profile.">Royal Wulff</a></b>
  </div>

  <div class="comment-content">
    <div class="author"><div class="picture">
  <a href="/users/royal-wulff" title="View user profile."><img src="/sites/all/themes/newsflash/images/bagicon.png" alt="Royal Wulff&#039;s picture" title="Royal Wulff&#039;s picture"  /></a></div>
</div><div class="author"></div>
    <p>The difficulty of mining is adjusted so that a new "block" appears about every 10 minutes. The reward for mining a block is (currently) 25 bit coins. That's how new bit coins come into existence, as a reward for the miner who invested computational effort into confirming a block.</p>
<p>Even if the state threw all their resources into it and defeated the difficulty adjustment, the maximum number of bitcoins allowed to be generated is 21 million.</p>
<p>After that, miners do not get awarded new bitcoins. Instead, they make bitcoins based on transaction fees for validating transactions.</p>

  </div>
  <div class="links"></div>
