<div class="non_toggle_area" id="comment-3334561">
  <div class="non_toggle_label">
       <span class="scomments_info">Sat, 03/16/2013 - 01:07 | <a href="/news/2013-03-15/guest-post-what-world-bitcoin#comment-3334561" class="active">3334561</a></span>
              <b><a href="/users/kennard" title="View user profile.">kennard</a></b>
  </div>

  <div class="comment-content">
    <div class="author"><div class="picture">
  <a href="/users/kennard" title="View user profile."><img src="http://www.zerohedge.com/sites/default/files/pictures/picture-10300.png" alt="kennard&#039;s picture" title="kennard&#039;s picture"  /></a></div>
</div><div class="author"></div>
    <p>re: "foreign financial account"</p>
<p>If your 'allocated' 400-ounce London Good Delivery gold bar is held by, say, Via Mat, a warehousing company that is not a bank or trust company, in their London vault and you hold merely a warehouse receipt, then I don't believe that you have a "financial account", foreign or domestic. The contract is a bailment, just as anyone would have with a warehouse where they may store their furniture. Let's say that you are transferred from London to New York for a year and put some of your household possessions in a London warehouse until you return. If you leave a 400-ounce gold bar in a desk drawer among your possessions, does that mean that you have a 'foreign financial account' while you are resident in the U.S.? You do not.</p>
<p>A Bitcoin is an account, not a warehouse bailment. The bitcoin account is not 'foreign', however. So the Bitcoin is outside the compliance bludgeoning rule that you cite.</p>
<p>Worldwide income from any asset, including precious metals and Bitcoins, must be reported by a U.S. taxpayer. Therefore, falling outside your rule does not exempt anyoone from reporting income from Bitcoin trading; it merely reduces the risk associated with evading that income. If the IRS can subpoena Bitcoin trading records, or if they should happen to fall into the IRS' hands, then the assessment risk will outweigh the reward.</p>

  </div>
  <div class="links"></div>
